<org.eclipse.epf.uma:TaskDescription xmi:version="2.0" xmlns:xmi="http://www.omg.org/XMI" xmlns:org.eclipse.epf.uma="http://www.eclipse.org/epf/uma/1.0.6/uma.ecore" xmlns:rmc="http://www.ibm.com/rmc" rmc:version="7.5.1" xmlns:epf="http://www.eclipse.org/epf" epf:version="1.5.1" xmi:id="-lJahxhv7j8HxXyHwlzD3uw" name=",_zPcTUKZKEeCmzNtTCfivQw" guid="-lJahxhv7j8HxXyHwlzD3uw" version="7.5.1">
  <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    ISO 26262, volume 8, clause 9 defines the guidance for generic aspects of verification planning which should be followed.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    In order to detect systematic faults within the implementation during systems integration, various test methods must be&#xD;
    selected that cover a variety of aspects of test and verification.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The selection of the application&amp;nbsp;feasible methods are detailed in the steps section.&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
  <sections xmi:id="_7BteUKZhEeCmzNtTCfivQw" name="Select methods for the Correctness of implementation of system design specification, technical and functional safety requirements" guid="_7BteUKZhEeCmzNtTCfivQw">
    <sectionDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    To ensure the correctness of implementation of functional safety requirements, all&amp;nbsp;the following types of test are&#xD;
    highly recommended at all ASIL levels:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;blockquote style=&quot;MARGIN-RIGHT: 0px&quot; dir=&quot;ltr&quot;>&#xD;
    &lt;p>&#xD;
        Requirements-based test, this recommended for items of any ASIL.&#xD;
    &lt;/p>&#xD;
    &lt;p>&#xD;
        Fault injection test, this is recommended for items with an ASIL of A or B and highly recommended for items with an&#xD;
        ASIL of C or D .&#xD;
    &lt;/p>&#xD;
    &lt;p>&#xD;
        Back to back tests, this is recommended for items with an ASIL of&amp;nbsp;B or C&amp;nbsp;and highly recommended for items&#xD;
        with an ASIL of D .&#xD;
    &lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;/blockquote>&#xD;
&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;>&#xD;
    Requirements based testing is used to test against functional and non-functional (quality of service) requirements.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;>&#xD;
    Fault injection test uses special means to introduce faults into the item. This can be done within the item via a&#xD;
    special test interface or specially prepared elements or communication devices. The method is often used to improve the&#xD;
    test coverage of the safety requirements, because during normal operation safety mechanisms are not invoked&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; align=&quot;justify&quot;>&#xD;
    Back to back testing compares the outputs of the test object to the outputs of a simulation model when both are&#xD;
    subjected to the same set of inputs. This technique is common when using model based testing&amp;nbsp;techniques, comparing&#xD;
    specification scenarios captured in sequence diagrams to the actual outputs from the code.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; align=&quot;justify&quot;>&#xD;
    This summary is based upon &quot;Table 14 Correctness of implementation of functional safety requirements&quot;, located in ISO&#xD;
    26262, volume 4, clause 8.4.3.2.1 .&#xD;
&lt;/p></sectionDescription>
  </sections>
  <sections xmi:id="_OB8OAKZiEeCmzNtTCfivQw" name="Select methods for the correctness of functional performance, accuracy and timing of safety mechanisms" guid="_OB8OAKZiEeCmzNtTCfivQw">
    <sectionDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    Please refer to &quot;Table 10-&amp;nbsp;Correctness of functional performance, accuracy and timing of safety mechanisms&quot;,&#xD;
    located in ISO 26262, volume 4, clause 8.4.3.2.2, for details of recommendations for these test types against ASIL. In&#xD;
    summary the types of test mentioned are.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;blockquote style=&quot;MARGIN-RIGHT: 0px&quot; dir=&quot;ltr&quot;>&#xD;
    &lt;p>&#xD;
        Back to back tests&#xD;
    &lt;/p>&#xD;
    &lt;p>&#xD;
        Performance tests&#xD;
    &lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;/blockquote>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Both types of test are recommended for ASIL B or C and highly recommended for ASIL D.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Back to back test compare the output from the item being tested to the output of a simulation model to the same set of&#xD;
    inputs. This is to detect the difference between the model and implementation. This is a&amp;nbsp;common technique in model&#xD;
    based development for software.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Performance test can verify that the safety mechanisms in the system respond according the to the intended quality of&#xD;
    service requirements.&#xD;
&lt;/p></sectionDescription>
  </sections>
